VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1) On 2/11/23 at approximately 0057 hours, I, TFC. Davis was on patrol in the area northbound Route 13 @ Bateman St.,Salisbury, Wicomico County, Maryland. While in that area, I observed a white Nissan Altima bearing Maryland registration 9DZ8469 that was stopped in the right merge lane (Lane 3) with faced with a green traffic signal for approximately 10 seconds. As I approached the vehicle, I positioned myunmarked patrol vehicle E-16 directly behind the vehicle andactivated my emergency equipment conducting a traffic stop on the vehicle. PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2) I approached the vehicle using a driver side approach.At that time, I made contact with the driver, who I identified as Thorne Hurt. Hurt appeared to be confused and dazed. While speaking to Hurt, I was able todetectthe strong odor of Marijuana along with the faint odor of an alcoholic beverage coming from the inside of the vehicle. Iobserved Hurtseyes to be bloodshot and glassy. Upon running a license and wanted check of Hurt, it revealed he was wanted through Parole and Probation. On my second approach, I asked Hurt to exit the vehicle to at which time I detained him for being wanted along with conducting a probable cause search of the vehicle. While out of the vehicle, I continued detected theodor of an alcoholic beverage coming from Hurt.Hurt was placed in the front passenger seat of my patrol vehicle. A probable cause search of the vehicle was completed Inside the passenger compartment of the vehicle two digital scales along with numerous zip lock baggies were located. I then located in the trunk of the vehicle a blue Food-lion grocery bag with a single triple sealed k-pak containing suspected Marijuana labeled what appeared to be ICE. Hurt then also placed under arrest for Marijuana in the amount over civil use. Also located in the vehicle was an empty bottle of Upon returning to my patrol vehicle, I was able to detect the odor of an alcoholic beverage that was not their prior to putting Hurt in. Hurt was transported to the Salisbury Barrack for processing. Upon our arrival at the barrack a secondary search of Hurt was completed. PRE-ARREST SCREENING(PHASE 3) The evaluationwereperformed in MSP Salisbury holding cell. Lighting conditions consisted of the cells lights. It was level and free from any debris. Hurt was asked the following questions: Contacts/ Glasses- No Medication- Yes Injuries- Visible right leg injury HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS The first test administered was the Horizontal Gaze Nystagmus (HGN) test. Hurtwas instructed to keep his arms at his sides and his head straight throughout the course of the test. I held a stimulus (pen) twelve (12) to fifteen (15) inches in front of Hurts face, slightly above the eye level. I instructed Hurtto follow the tip of the pen with his eyes, without moving his head. Starting with the left eye, I moved the pen from side to side, two (2) full passes, to see if Hurts eyes tracked equally, which they did. Both pupils were noted to be of equal size. I moved the stimulus (pen) in the same manner checking for the first (2) clues, Lack of Smooth pursuit in both eyes. Both eyes exhibited a lack of smooth pursuit. I moved the stimulus (pen) from the center out to maximum deviation, starting with Hurts left eye, to check for the next (2) clues, Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation. I observed both clues. I moved the pen from the center to approximately forty-five (45) degrees very slowly, starting with the left eye to check for the last (2) clues, On Set of Nystagmus Prior to (45) degrees. Each eye was checked with both clues being present. During the test, I observed the following clues: 1. Lack of Smooth Pursuit - Present in both eyes 2. Distinct and Sustained Nystagmus at Maximum Deviation - Present in both eyes 3. Onset of Nystagmus Prior to 45 Degrees - Present in both eyes Total Clues: 6 out of 6 Vertical- Not Present WALK AND TURN Not conducted due to leg injury. ONE LEG STAND Not conducted due to leg injury. F to T I then asked Hurt what his highest level of education was which he responded with 10th grade. I asked Hurt if he knew his alphabet which he responded that he did. I asked Hurt to say the alphabet from F to T without singing. Hurt failed to stop at T going to Z. Hurt began singing the alphabet while doing so. 59 - 36 I asked Hurt if he could count to 100 which he stated he could. I asked Hurt to count from 59 to 36. Hurt stopped at 39 instead of 36 as instructed. ARREST: Based on the following, I had reason to believe Hurt was driving a vehicle under the influence of alcohol: * Odor of an alcoholic beverage emanating from breath and person. * Eyes blood shot and glassy. * I observed signs of impairment as he performed SFST. * Empty bottle of Liquor in vehicle. * Unable to remain awake inside cell. During my investigation, based on my training, knowledge, and experience as a Maryland State Trooper, I determined Hurt was impaired by alcoholand could not operate a vehicle safely at 0229 hours. 20 MINUTE OBSERVATION PERIOD: Nothing to report. INTOXIMETER RESULT: I gave Hurt a copy of the DR-15 Advice of Rights form to read along as I read it to him. Upon completion, Hurt refused the test. All contraband was processed in accordance to Maryland State Police Policy. The marijuana total weight was 515.4 grams and was placed into Barrack E temporary storage. I was able to identify the marijuana due to my training, knowledge, and experience as a Maryland State Trooper. Due to the amount of Marijuana, the individual plastic baggies, and digital scales located, it is indicative of the possessor to have intent to distribute the controlled dangerous substance. I was able to identify this due to my training, knowledge, and experience as a Maryland State Trooper. Hurts cell phone was seized pending a search warrant. Hurt was transported to Wicomico Detention center for his initial appearance before a Wicomico County District Court Commissioner. Each and all the above events occurred in Wicomico County, Maryland. Case closed by the arrest.
